1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1376":"1376","1431":"1431","1364":"1364","about 1383":"circa 1383","1439":"1439","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Haslington, Cheshire, England":"Haslington, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1364–6 December 1431":"1364–6 December 1431","1364–1431":"1364–1431","1374–Male":"1374–Deceased","1376–1431":"1376–1431","1378–Male":"1378–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1361–Female":"1361–Deceased","1383–1439":"1383–1439","1335–1404":"1335–1404","1337–1384":"1337–1384","about 1382":"about 1382","1374":"1374","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","6 December 1431":"6 December 1431","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1376":"1376","1431":"1431","1364":"1364","about 1383":"about 1383","1439":"1439","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Haslington, Cheshire, England":"Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vernon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vernon in Eure, France, named from the Gaulish element <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + the Gallo-Roman locative suffix <i>-o</i> (genitive <i>-ōnis</i>).","French: habitational name from the same place as in 1 above or from any of several other places in France with the same name and etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Varnon","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Vernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Jacob","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very popular among the Puritans from the 16th century onwards, and has again been widely used since the 1990s.  Compare  James ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baron Jacob Vernon was born in 1364, in Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Vernon, was 29 and his mother, Elena Duckinfield, was 27. He married Margaret Minshull about 1382, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 6 December 1431, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1364–6 December 1431":"1364–6. detsember 1431","1364–1431":"1364–1431","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1376–1431":"1376–1431","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1361–Female":"1361–Surnud","1383–1439":"1383–1439","1335–1404":"1335–1404","1337–1384":"1337–1384","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1374":"1374","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","6 December 1431":"6. detsember 1431","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1376":"1376","1431":"1431","13